-- French Stocks; BNP Paribas, Societe Generale, Total, Faurecia Are Active
-- Francesca Angelini
-- 2010-07-08T16:09:07Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-07-07/dl-software-ldc-prismaflex-and-peugeot-citroen-french-equity-preview.html

          
          
             France’s benchmark  CAC 40 Index 
advanced 54.81, or 1.6 percent, to 3,538.3 in Paris. The  SBF 120
index  climbed 1.5 percent.  
 The following companies’ shares were among the most active
in France today. Symbols are in parentheses.  
 Alcatel-Lucent SA  (ALU FP) climbed 2.8 percent to 2.15
euros, rising for the third day. The shares were raised to
“buy” from “add” at Alphavalue by equity analyst  Jean-Michel Salvador .  
 BNP Paribas SA  (BNP FP), France’s largest bank, increased
3.3 percent to 49.57 euros and  Societe Generale SA  (GLE FP), the
country’s second-biggest bank by market value, rose 3.2 percent
to 38.78 euros. Both are among the 91 European banks that are
subject to stress tests, the Committee of European Banking
Supervisors wrote in a statement.  
 Strategists at Credit Suisse Group AG raised their
recommendation for banks to “benchmark,” saying European
sovereign-debt risk is overstated, bank stocks are undervalued
and the European Union stress tests “may be a positive
catalyst.”  
 Faurecia SA  (EO FP) jumped 3.3 percent to 14.91 euros,
rising for a fifth day. Europe’s biggest maker of car interiors
will set up joint ventures with Chinese companies Geely and
Limin to supply interior systems and automotive exteriors to all
Geely brands in China.  
 Renault SA  (RNO FP), France’s second-biggest automaker,
rose 2.9 percent to 33.1 euros. First-half vehicle sales gained
22 percent as European government incentives and resurgent
emerging markets spurred demand, the company said today in a
statement.  
 Analyst  Alexis Albert  at Nomura Holdings Inc. upgraded the
shares to “buy” from “neutral,” recommending that the
general consensus for the company was too low.  
 Total SA  (FP FP), Europe’s second-biggest oil producer,
increased 2.2 percent to 38.04 euros as crude rose for a second
day in New York. UBS AG raised the shared to “buy” from
“neutral.”  
